title: For Sale:  12g Mobil Choke Set (for Berretta, Benelli, CZ and Huglu)
location: Hartford, 60 miles S. of Topeka, Topeka, Kansas
postcontent: Got these Italian made FACTORY chokes with a Huglu Custom Shotgun this year.  Shot about 5-10 shots through a few of them before getting new Carlson tubes in to replace these.  They are stainless steel flush mount, no frills tubes that look just like the Carlson/Beretta flush mount tubes you'll see going for about $20 each.  The set has FOUR chokes: Full (4/4), IM (3/4), M (2/4) and IC (1/4) and like all factory chokes... shooting steel shot through the Full and Improved Modified chokes is a "no-no".  Steel through the Modified or IC is ok though (and are said to give the same patterns as lead Full and IM respectively due the the tighter nature of steel shot over lead in general).The set comes with a choke wrench and fitted, black plastic box to hold the four chokes (and wrench) as well as a few Q-tips or patches in a nice small box-- fits easily in my shotgun case beside the barrel (where I wrap it in a oil cloth).  When done shooting, it's always a good idea to pull the chokes, lube them and the barrel (Q-tips work perfect) BEFORE leaving the feild.  Set is clean and look "as new".  All four chokes fit both my barrels (in my over/under) well, but the IM choke is a bit tight going down in my top barrel-- but still threads fine by hand and shot fine when I used it.  These have the standard end-notch ID system so you can easily see what choke is in the barrel without having to remove it.A nice clean set and for those wanting matched chokes for a "mobil choke" shotgun, here's a way to have two tubes (for each choke-- i.e. good for double barrels).  My new Carslons shoot no better than these did- but they look cooler (and cost a LOT more).  So I probably should have just kept these and been happy.  But I don't need these now so here they are and I'll ship them for a flat $50 OR meet nearby Emporia, KS (or around SE Kansas on a weekend) for $45.  Thanks Armslisters!!!

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P238 .380 ACP Pistol, Engraved Slide, White Pearlite Grips, Night Sights, Black Frame – Sig Sauer 238-380-ESW
postcontent: We have hundreds of other guns currently IN STOCK, and offer some of Utah’s lowest prices! For a complete listing of our current inventory, and to purchase this and other guns online, please be sure to VISIT US ON THE WEB AT:   ***** TooeleShootingSupply.com *****   Not Your Average “Mouse” Gun. The Sig Sauer P238 is different from most other .380 “pocket” pistols on the market today. In terms of size and shape, the P238 is very similar to other comparable micro .380’s. Instead of a polymer frame, however, the Sig Sauer P238 uses an alloy frame with a single action design, and is almost identical in appearance to the legendary Colt Mustang.   The Sig Sauer P238 operates with a locked-breech short recoil action. The hammer must be cocked either manually, or by the action of the slide, to fire each shot. The advantage to this method of operation is two- fold. First and foremost, similar to the Colt 1911 or Mustang, the Sig Sauer P238 has a superior trigger pull when compared to similarly sized double action only designs like the Ruger LCP, Smith & Wesson Bodyguard or Kel-Tec P3AT. In turn, this leads to greater accuracy. Second, the P238’s single action design allows Sig Sauer to incorporate a high ride beavertail grip frame, which leads to greater control under recoil by safely placing the shooter’s hand higher along the bore axis.   In addition to being a great-looking pistol, the Sig Sauer P238 is much easier to load than other micro pistols on the market. For shooters that do not possess strong hands, the P238’s smooth and easy slide is one of its most highly appreciated features. There are also positive vertical serrations on the back of the slide that further enhance loading or unloading.   The Sig Sauer P238 slide locks to the rear on an empty magazine, and the slide latch release is easy to reach with the thumb of the shooting hand. Similarly, the P238 has a user friendly manual thumb safety which further enhances shooter usability. The Sig Sauer P238 has stippling on the grips for a secure hold while firing the pistol. As mentioned, the frame has a generous beavertail to protect the web between the shooter’s thumb and trigger finger, and the hammer recesses into the beavertail section, to avoid any chance of hammer or slide-bite while firing the pistol. The Sig Sauer P238 is a very compact design, and while it may be slightly heavier than the polymer .380ACP pistols on the market, it is just as small.   We currently have this firearm in stock, and have it priced to sell quickly for just $649. title: For Sale:  Parker Brothers SxS shotgun
postcontent: Early Parker Brothers 12 Guage SxS shotgun.  Based on the Serial #47872, it was produced in 1886.  The barrels are "twist" steel and barrel weight is 4#9oz.  The frame size is "0" with a small "2" next to it.  The grade is not stamped above the serial number, so I'm not sure.  The serial number on the water table, barrel lug, and forearm steel match.  The external hammers and trigger mechanisms function as they should, the hammer springs are stiff.  The break open action is solid, although the shotgun has definitely seen some time in the field.  The stock is in decent shape and has a Parker Brothers butt plate.  the forearm is in poor shape with lots of scratches and dings.  No visible cracks in the wood parts.  The 32" barrels are "twist" steel.  The bores show surface blemishes, likely rust, but I couldn't get a good look due to barrel length.Please email any additional questions.  Very cool classic Parker Brothers Side x Side shotgun.
